T1  - Network Effects Revisited: The Role of Strong Ties in Technology Selection
AU  - Suarez, Fernando F.
Y1  - 2005/08/01
PY  - 2005
DA  - 2005/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2005.17843947
DO  - 10.5465/amj.2005.17843947
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 710
EP  - 720
VL  - 48
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This paper extends the theory of network effects by moving beyond the traditional treatment of the installed base of a technology as composed of ?N? identical users, each having the same effect on the rest of the users. Borrowing from social network theory, I propose the concept of strong-ties network effects as a key determinant of technology adoption in cases where several technologies compete. A discrete-choice model was tested in the wireless telecommunications industry.
AB  - This paper extends the theory of network effects by moving beyond the traditional treatment of the installed base of a technology as composed of ?N? identical users, each having the same effect on the rest of the users. Borrowing from social network theory, I propose the concept of strong-ties network effects as a key determinant of technology adoption in cases where several technologies compete. A discrete-choice model was tested in the wireless telecommunications industry.
